18
00:00:55,920 --> 00:00:59,200
 and to encourage the study and implementation

19
00:00:59,200 --> 00:01:02,360
 of pastoral theology that is biblical,

20
00:01:02,360 --> 00:01:04,840
 relevant, and contextual.

21
00:01:04,840 --> 00:01:08,420
 For our speaker today, for our keynote speaker today,

22
00:01:08,420 --> 00:01:10,160
 we are very privileged to have

23
00:01:10,160 --> 00:01:13,280
 Reverend Dr. Peter Phillips here with us today,

24
00:01:13,280 --> 00:01:15,500
 who will be sharing with us on a topic

25
00:01:15,500 --> 00:01:18,020
 of preaching in the digital age.

26
00:01:18,020 --> 00:01:19,720
 If you scan the QR code here,

27
00:01:19,720 --> 00:01:21,960
 you will be able to download our pamphlet

28
00:01:21,960 --> 00:01:23,800
 for today's program.

29
00:01:23,800 --> 00:01:27,360
 Dr. Phillips is currently at Cliff College, UK,

30
00:01:27,360 --> 00:01:30,520
 supervising PhD students and building

31
00:01:30,520 --> 00:01:32,720
 their digital theology programs,

32
00:01:32,720 --> 00:01:36,200
 while also serving as a Methodist ministry

33
00:01:36,200 --> 00:01:38,320
 at the Thames Valley Circuit.

34
00:01:38,320 --> 00:01:41,720
 Pete had served as a research fellow

35
00:01:41,720 --> 00:01:44,720
 and director at the Center of Digital Theology

36
00:01:44,720 --> 00:01:48,280
 in Durham University, as well as the director

37
00:01:48,280 --> 00:01:51,040
 of the Center of Digital Theology

38
00:01:51,040 --> 00:01:54,320
 and tutor at Spurgeon's College.

39
00:01:54,320 --> 00:01:57,680
 Pete's current research focuses on the impact

40
00:01:57,680 --> 00:02:00,240
 of digital culture on theology

41
00:02:00,240 --> 00:02:04,520
 and on contemporary religious practice.

42
00:02:04,520 --> 00:02:08,160
 As for our respondent, we're very grateful

43
00:02:08,160 --> 00:02:11,800
 to have Reverend Mike Liu here today.

44
00:02:11,800 --> 00:02:14,480
 Reverend Mike Liu is not only a pastor

45
00:02:14,480 --> 00:02:18,240
 who had over 20 years of pastoral experiences,

46
00:02:18,240 --> 00:02:22,060
 but he is actually also an AI enthusiast,

47
00:02:22,060 --> 00:02:24,840
 working as an AI training instructor,

48
00:02:24,840 --> 00:02:27,740
 equipping both the church and the general public

49
00:02:27,740 --> 00:02:31,760
 on how to better utilize various AI tools.

50
00:02:31,760 --> 00:02:35,600
 My wife was actually a student in one of Mike's class,

51
00:02:35,600 --> 00:02:38,040
 trying to figure out how AI can help

52
00:02:38,040 --> 00:02:40,940
 with parenting and in home activities,

53
00:02:40,940 --> 00:02:42,560
 and that's been going well.

54
00:02:42,560 --> 00:02:45,760
 Reverend Liu had also been hosting workshops

55
00:02:45,760 --> 00:02:48,200
 on issues related to pastoral care

56
00:02:48,200 --> 00:02:50,120
 and artificial intelligence,

57
00:02:50,120 --> 00:02:52,520
 now also a pastor at Calvin Tong Church

58
00:02:52,520 --> 00:02:56,760
 of the Chinese CNMA and Christian Alliance College Church.

59
00:02:56,760 --> 00:03:00,120
 So, after a keynote lecture and a response,

60
00:03:00,120 --> 00:03:03,680
 we'll invite both Dr. Phillips and Reverend Liu

61
00:03:03,680 --> 00:03:06,580
 to come up on the stage for some Q&A,

62
00:03:06,580 --> 00:03:09,080
 where you, as participants, will be able

63
00:03:09,080 --> 00:03:12,120
 to send in your questions via the WhatsApp code

64
00:03:12,120 --> 00:03:14,120
 or use the mic in the middle.

65
00:03:14,120 --> 00:03:17,560
 Now, without further ado, let's give a round of applause

66
00:03:17,560 --> 00:03:19,520
 and welcome Dr. Phillips.

67
00:03:19,520 --> 00:03:22,680
 (audience applauding)

68
00:03:22,680 --> 00:03:33,440
 - Good morning, everybody.

69
00:03:33,440 --> 00:03:34,440
 - Good morning.

70
00:03:34,440 --> 00:03:36,800
 - It's good to be here with you this morning

71
00:03:36,800 --> 00:03:38,640
 and to explore this topic.

72
00:03:38,640 --> 00:03:41,720
 I have to say, I thought I was going

73
00:03:41,720 --> 00:03:43,240
 to be more revolutionary.

74
00:03:44,080 --> 00:03:48,440
 I thought that I was going to say something groundbreaking

75
00:03:48,440 --> 00:03:52,040
 in this subject, and instead,

76
00:03:52,040 --> 00:03:54,400
 it's something quite different than I expected.

77
00:03:54,400 --> 00:03:57,640
 That's probably the process that we all go through

78
00:03:57,640 --> 00:03:59,120
 when we prepare a sermon,

79
00:03:59,120 --> 00:04:03,400
 when we think about what are we gonna do

80
00:04:03,400 --> 00:04:04,680
 and how will we do it,

81
00:04:04,680 --> 00:04:07,400
 and then we begin to engage with God

82
00:04:07,400 --> 00:04:09,440
 and find that things go a different way.

83
00:04:11,440 --> 00:04:13,800
 Thank you very much for the invitation

84
00:04:13,800 --> 00:04:15,080
 to give this lecture.

85
00:04:15,080 --> 00:04:19,240
 I've been preaching and teaching various courses

86
00:04:19,240 --> 00:04:21,960
 on preaching for almost 40 years now.

87
00:04:21,960 --> 00:04:23,180
 I feel very old.

88
00:04:23,180 --> 00:04:27,240
 But I'm not an expert in homiletics.

89
00:04:27,240 --> 00:04:31,720
 I'm just an ordinary Methodist minister

90
00:04:31,720 --> 00:04:34,500
 who is seeking constantly to find out

91
00:04:34,500 --> 00:04:37,760
 what God wants to share with my congregations.

92
00:04:38,900 --> 00:04:43,180
 How do I impart his word to them?

93
00:04:43,180 --> 00:04:47,980
 How do we all grow in that word

94
00:04:47,980 --> 00:04:51,520
 and seek to be the people God has created us to be?

95
00:04:51,520 --> 00:04:56,940
 How does my preaching in its own little way

96
00:04:56,940 --> 00:05:00,860
 inaugurate something of the kingdom of God afresh

97
00:05:00,860 --> 00:05:02,500
 wherever I am preaching?

98
00:05:02,500 --> 00:05:07,700
 But this is a lecture, not a preach.

99
00:05:07,700 --> 00:05:08,900
 So let's move on.

100
00:05:08,900 --> 00:05:15,660
 I hope you like the metaverse Jesus.

101
00:05:15,660 --> 00:05:18,320
 It's a very scary picture.

102
00:05:18,320 --> 00:05:26,300
 Preaching is both an important and complex part

103
00:05:26,300 --> 00:05:28,340
 of the worship life of the church.

104
00:05:28,340 --> 00:05:33,780
 Indeed, some aspect of using long-form presentation

105
00:05:33,780 --> 00:05:36,660
 to instruct and persuade people

106
00:05:36,660 --> 00:05:39,440
 stretches back to Israel's prophets

107
00:05:39,440 --> 00:05:42,420
 and beyond them to the patriarchs

108
00:05:42,420 --> 00:05:46,420
 and appears in numerous religious traditions.

109
00:05:46,420 --> 00:05:50,720
 Confucius, of course, used a form of preaching

110
00:05:50,720 --> 00:05:53,700
 to outline the basic goodness of humanity,

111
00:05:53,700 --> 00:05:58,400
 outline moral teaching, develop appropriate moral conduct.

112
00:05:58,400 --> 00:06:04,000
 For the church fathers,

113
00:06:05,100 --> 00:06:08,500
 preaching became an important means for evangelism,

114
00:06:08,500 --> 00:06:11,260
 for discipleship, for cohesion.

115
00:06:11,260 --> 00:06:16,580
 In his book on Christian doctrine, De Doctrina Christiana,

116
00:06:16,580 --> 00:06:18,760
 St. Augustine talked of the importance

117
00:06:18,760 --> 00:06:21,380
 of the preaching ministry of the church

118
00:06:21,380 --> 00:06:25,580
 to instruct, to delight, to persuade.

119
00:06:25,580 --> 00:06:31,320
 In other words, the goal of preaching is multifaceted.

120
00:06:33,220 --> 00:06:36,420
 In the church, preaching is about the exegesis

121
00:06:36,420 --> 00:06:39,220
 of the word of God, the Bible,

122
00:06:39,220 --> 00:06:43,740
 harking back to those prophets and leaders in Israel

123
00:06:43,740 --> 00:06:48,120
 who brought the word of God to his people,

124
00:06:48,120 --> 00:06:50,980
 who said, "This is what the Lord has said."

125
00:06:50,980 --> 00:06:55,900
 So today, preaching will continue to include

126
00:06:55,900 --> 00:06:57,740
 the instruction of God's people

127
00:06:57,740 --> 00:07:01,500
 in the content and purpose of scripture.

128
00:07:01,500 --> 00:07:04,720
 In whatever culture that sermon is preached,

129
00:07:04,720 --> 00:07:10,180
 usually preachers will take an assigned passage

130
00:07:10,180 --> 00:07:13,980
 and perhaps explore aspects of what that passage tells us

131
00:07:13,980 --> 00:07:18,980
 about its immediate context, historical and contemporary,

132
00:07:18,980 --> 00:07:22,300
 what it's meant to different audiences in the past

133
00:07:22,300 --> 00:07:23,320
 and what it might mean

134
00:07:23,320 --> 00:07:26,080
 within our own contemporary society today.

135
00:07:26,080 --> 00:07:31,380
 Notice already the word skill,

136
00:07:31,380 --> 00:07:34,060
 the rhetorical skill of the preacher.

137
00:07:34,060 --> 00:07:37,300
 One of Augustine's key influences

138
00:07:37,300 --> 00:07:39,300
 was Cicero, the Roman orator.

139
00:07:39,300 --> 00:07:43,580
 But we've also begun to bring in the Bible

140
00:07:43,580 --> 00:07:46,680
 and to note that the reception of the sermon

141
00:07:46,680 --> 00:07:50,340
 by an audience is also of prime importance.

142
00:07:50,340 --> 00:08:00,120
 Of course, long-form communication

143
00:08:00,120 --> 00:08:02,220
 doesn't always mean words.

144
00:08:02,220 --> 00:08:05,660
 Although the sheer weight of words

145
00:08:05,660 --> 00:08:08,660
 is a heavy burden on the sermonic tradition.

146
00:08:08,660 --> 00:08:12,700
 When we preachers get talking,

147
00:08:12,700 --> 00:08:14,520
 we like to carry on talking.

148
00:08:14,520 --> 00:08:20,120
 Patriarchs, prophets, priests

149
00:08:20,120 --> 00:08:22,020
 are all shown in the Bible

150
00:08:22,020 --> 00:08:25,020
 to have used whatever source of communication

151
00:08:25,020 --> 00:08:27,900
 fit best into the situation

152
00:08:27,900 --> 00:08:29,820
 or into their own character.

153
00:08:30,720 --> 00:08:34,560
 Jesus used parables, healing miracles,

154
00:08:34,560 --> 00:08:39,560
 acts of defiance, meals, resurrections, homilies,

155
00:08:39,560 --> 00:08:45,680
 Bible readings, exorcisms, alongside long speeches.

156
00:08:45,680 --> 00:08:51,440
 With Augustine's conversion,

157
00:08:51,440 --> 00:08:54,180
 you'll remember it's a book that spoke to him.

158
00:08:54,180 --> 00:08:58,760
 "Tolilege, tolilege," he heard a voice saying.

159
00:08:58,760 --> 00:09:00,960
 "Pick me up and read me."

160
00:09:00,960 --> 00:09:06,680
 John Wesley's choice to become more vile

161
00:09:06,680 --> 00:09:09,040
 as a Methodist minister in the UK,

162
00:09:09,040 --> 00:09:11,580
 back in Britain back in the day,

163
00:09:11,580 --> 00:09:16,040
 to go out to the coal miners in east of Bristol

164
00:09:16,040 --> 00:09:17,760
 to take the gospel to them.

165
00:09:17,760 --> 00:09:20,740
 Indeed, street preaching happened

166
00:09:20,740 --> 00:09:22,540
 as missionaries came to Hong Kong

167
00:09:22,540 --> 00:09:25,760
 and local Hong Kong preachers continue

168
00:09:25,760 --> 00:09:29,000
 the ministry songs on the streets of Kowloon today

169
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:31,000
 as I've experienced this weekend.

170
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:36,720
 So too, the tradition continues

171
00:09:36,720 --> 00:09:39,960
 to celebrate plural forms of communication,

172
00:09:39,960 --> 00:09:42,120
 not just words.

173
00:09:42,120 --> 00:09:45,460
 Through the ministries of art and song,

174
00:09:45,460 --> 00:09:49,920
 creativity, performance, healing, reflection, and meditation

175
00:09:49,920 --> 00:09:52,280
 not least through Ignatian practices

176
00:09:52,280 --> 00:09:55,600
 of Lectio Divina or Ignatian contemplation.

177
00:09:56,600 --> 00:10:01,600
 Dare I say it, words are sometimes not the best way

178
00:10:01,600 --> 00:10:05,300
 to address what God is telling us to communicate.

179
00:10:05,300 --> 00:10:14,560
 But nor is communication ever a one-way process,

180
00:10:14,560 --> 00:10:16,040
 apart from when you're giving a lecture

181
00:10:16,040 --> 00:10:17,880
 in a prestigious theological college.

182
00:10:17,880 --> 00:10:25,200
 It's not a preacher telling an audience what to do.

183
00:10:26,200 --> 00:10:29,920
 It's more likely to be a communication process

184
00:10:29,920 --> 00:10:31,840
 where the speaker has some idea

185
00:10:31,840 --> 00:10:35,520
 of the content they're trying to communicate.

186
00:10:35,520 --> 00:10:40,640
 But the listener, you, have your own interpretation

187
00:10:40,640 --> 00:10:45,240
 on what you hear the preacher to be saying,

188
00:10:45,240 --> 00:10:49,860
 what they're going to do about it in life.

189
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:55,920
 Moreover, both preacher and congregation

190
00:10:55,920 --> 00:10:58,880
 might have different understandings of the word

191
00:10:58,880 --> 00:11:01,300
 which the communication is based on.

192
00:11:01,300 --> 00:11:06,320
 It's all more complicated

193
00:11:06,320 --> 00:11:09,560
 than telling a congregation what God is saying.

194
00:11:09,560 --> 00:11:14,480
 It's not, thus spake the Lord to the preacher

195
00:11:14,480 --> 00:11:16,340
 and the congregation obeyed.

196
00:11:17,780 --> 00:11:22,140
 The Holy Spirit, the congregation, the Bible

197
00:11:22,140 --> 00:11:24,100
 might all have a lot to say

198
00:11:24,100 --> 00:11:26,880
 about what the sermon is meant to be doing.

199
00:11:26,880 --> 00:11:33,220
 And any sermon is likely to be a congregation, sorry,

200
00:11:33,220 --> 00:11:38,260
 to be a conversation between sender, receiver,

201
00:11:38,260 --> 00:11:40,020
 and everything in between.

202
00:11:45,420 --> 00:11:47,620
 Preaching according to Augustine

203
00:11:47,620 --> 00:11:50,700
 is also about seeking to delight the audience,

204
00:11:50,700 --> 00:11:54,380
 showing them the text,

205
00:11:54,380 --> 00:11:58,260
 bringing the text alive in their presence.

206
00:11:58,260 --> 00:12:04,380
 A good example of this is in one of Paul's earliest letters.

207
00:12:04,380 --> 00:12:09,880
 In Galatians 3, 1, Paul talks of his own preaching

208
00:12:09,880 --> 00:12:14,880
 as Christ crucified being portrayed or painted or penned

209
00:12:15,880 --> 00:12:20,040
 proagraphen, the Greek, before their very eyes.

210
00:12:20,040 --> 00:12:27,840
 He doesn't say it is as if Christ is crucified.

211
00:12:27,840 --> 00:12:33,480
 He says Christ is there, crucified in front of you.

212
00:12:33,480 --> 00:12:39,560
 In the slide, a picture painted by Lucas Cranach the Elder

213
00:12:39,560 --> 00:12:44,560
 in 1547 is of Luther here on the far right there.

214
00:12:45,560 --> 00:12:47,420
 Far left, sorry.

215
00:12:47,420 --> 00:12:53,920
 In the sermon, the words put the visual form.

216
00:12:53,920 --> 00:12:59,720
 Luther's left hand, palm down, holding the Bible,

217
00:12:59,720 --> 00:13:03,760
 grounded in the Bible, here at the bottom left-hand corner.

218
00:13:03,760 --> 00:13:10,120
 For Paul tells us, for faith, Paul tells us,

219
00:13:10,120 --> 00:13:13,360
 comes from hearing, hearing the word of God.

220
00:13:14,360 --> 00:13:17,080
 But surely this passage in Galatians isn't pointing

221
00:13:17,080 --> 00:13:19,780
 to a picture on the wall of the church in Galatia.

222
00:13:19,780 --> 00:13:23,840
 It's far too early for such a painting to have existed.

223
00:13:23,840 --> 00:13:28,760
 Neither Paul nor the Galatians were eyewitnesses

224
00:13:28,760 --> 00:13:31,840
 of the crucifixion, so what's happening here?

225
00:13:31,840 --> 00:13:36,920
 In some way, as in many forms of Romano-Hellenistic

226
00:13:36,920 --> 00:13:40,520
 street rhetoric of the time, the point was

227
00:13:40,520 --> 00:13:45,080
 that the repetition of the idea makes the idea come alive

228
00:13:45,080 --> 00:13:48,180
 in the listeners' hearts and minds.

229
00:13:48,180 --> 00:13:52,080
 The words turn the saying into an event

230
00:13:52,080 --> 00:13:54,620
 before their very eyes.

231
00:13:54,620 --> 00:13:57,680
 Not just tell them about Jesus crucified,

232
00:13:57,680 --> 00:14:01,220
 but performing that very act before them

233
00:14:01,220 --> 00:14:03,000
 in the words of the sermon,

234
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:05,760
 to enact it before their very eyes.

235
00:14:05,760 --> 00:14:10,340
 Paul believes, as he tells of Christ crucified,

236
00:14:10,340 --> 00:14:12,720
 that as he speaks and they listen,

237
00:14:12,720 --> 00:14:16,620
 they are invited to relive that event.

238
00:14:16,620 --> 00:14:21,560
 Let me go off message for a moment.

239
00:14:21,560 --> 00:14:24,720
 On Sunday morning, I was delighted to preach

240
00:14:24,720 --> 00:14:26,960
 at the Methodist International Church

241
00:14:26,960 --> 00:14:30,340
 in Wan Choy in Hong Kong.

242
00:14:30,340 --> 00:14:34,960
 And at that event, at that preach,

243
00:14:34,960 --> 00:14:39,480
 I was preaching on the prayer of Simeon and Anna

244
00:14:39,480 --> 00:14:41,400
 from Luke's Gospel.

245
00:14:41,400 --> 00:14:46,400
 And I used an icon from Novgorod in the ninth century,

246
00:14:46,400 --> 00:14:51,880
 sorry, 14th century, which had the main protagonists,

247
00:14:51,880 --> 00:14:53,560
 I should have put on the slide,

248
00:14:53,560 --> 00:14:57,160
 the main protagonists were on a screen, a picture of them.

249
00:14:57,160 --> 00:14:59,840
 And we went through, first of all,

250
00:14:59,840 --> 00:15:04,840
 from Joseph and Mary to Simeon and to Anna.

251
00:15:05,760 --> 00:15:10,760
 And I said, "Who are you in this icon?

252
00:15:10,760 --> 00:15:13,040
 "Who do you represent today?

253
00:15:13,040 --> 00:15:16,000
 "How do you come to this situation?"

254
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:19,200
 And then at the end of the sermon,

255
00:15:19,200 --> 00:15:21,440
 I felt that we needed to do something more

256
00:15:21,440 --> 00:15:23,040
 to reenact this.

257
00:15:23,040 --> 00:15:25,880
 And so I said to people,

258
00:15:25,880 --> 00:15:28,040
 well, I got the minister up and said,

259
00:15:28,040 --> 00:15:29,280
 can I move away from this?

260
00:15:29,280 --> 00:15:32,440
 I got ministers to come up and say,

261
00:15:32,440 --> 00:15:36,080
 here, you're Simeon, and one of their sisters,

262
00:15:36,080 --> 00:15:37,560
 here, you're Anna.

263
00:15:37,560 --> 00:15:40,280
 She got out of her seat and, you know, she was,

264
00:15:40,280 --> 00:15:41,520
 you don't see the microphone.

265
00:15:41,520 --> 00:15:44,600
 (audience laughing)

266
00:15:44,600 --> 00:15:47,520
 And then she got out of her seat and,

267
00:15:47,520 --> 00:15:48,640
 she, is it working?

268
00:15:48,640 --> 00:15:50,200
 Yeah, yeah, yeah.

269
00:15:50,200 --> 00:15:51,720
 And she got up out of her seat,

270
00:15:51,720 --> 00:15:53,680
 and then another two people came up

271
00:15:53,680 --> 00:15:56,720
 to be Joseph and Mary and what have you.

272
00:15:56,720 --> 00:15:59,280
 And I said to people in the congregation,

273
00:15:59,280 --> 00:16:01,800
 okay, so now we're gonna sing this song,

274
00:16:01,800 --> 00:16:03,240
 and while we're singing it,

275
00:16:03,240 --> 00:16:07,040
 why don't you come and stand with these people?

276
00:16:07,040 --> 00:16:09,400
 Come and reenact this moment,

277
00:16:09,400 --> 00:16:14,280
 the presentation of Jesus to the temple.

278
00:16:14,280 --> 00:16:15,880
 Be part of it.

279
00:16:15,880 --> 00:16:19,640
 Take your place within the biblical text itself,

280
00:16:19,640 --> 00:16:22,480
 within the reenactment of the text.

281
00:16:22,480 --> 00:16:24,920
 You see what I mean?

282
00:16:24,920 --> 00:16:27,040
 That it's a reen,

283
00:16:27,040 --> 00:16:31,240
 a sermon has to be a reenactment,

284
00:16:31,240 --> 00:16:34,360
 a reliving of the biblical text,

285
00:16:34,360 --> 00:16:39,360
 not just an exegetical academic study of a particular text.

286
00:16:39,360 --> 00:16:42,520
 The sermon is completely different.

287
00:16:42,520 --> 00:16:45,360
 It seeks to bring the text alive

288
00:16:45,360 --> 00:16:48,120
 in the presence of the congregation,

289
00:16:48,120 --> 00:16:49,800
 that it's the living word,

290
00:16:49,800 --> 00:16:52,200
 which breaks through the fourth wall

291
00:16:52,200 --> 00:16:54,720
 and enters into our presence as well.

292
00:16:54,720 --> 00:16:57,960
 Sorry, that was ad lib and it's not on,

293
00:16:57,960 --> 00:17:00,520
 and Michael, I'm sorry that you didn't,

294
00:17:00,520 --> 00:17:03,640
 you weren't made aware of that little ad lib beforehand,

295
00:17:03,640 --> 00:17:06,760
 but I hope you've explained that, thank you.

296
00:17:06,760 --> 00:17:16,760
 Preaching is not just a piece of text to be read out.

297
00:17:16,760 --> 00:17:22,480
 I do worry when the stewards at my church

298
00:17:22,480 --> 00:17:25,640
 say there's a spare sermon in the drawer in the vestry,

299
00:17:25,640 --> 00:17:29,800
 as if anyone can take it out,

300
00:17:29,800 --> 00:17:31,920
 and by reading it, give a sermon.

301
00:17:31,920 --> 00:17:37,560
 Preaching isn't a reading, that's a lecture, isn't it?

302
00:17:37,560 --> 00:17:43,800
 It's always a multi-modal, multi-dimensional interaction.

303
00:17:43,800 --> 00:17:48,440
 A God who chooses to interact with us,

304
00:17:48,440 --> 00:17:51,720
 to communicate, to reach out,

305
00:17:51,720 --> 00:17:55,720
 to engage, to love, Bible, preacher, faith,

306
00:17:55,720 --> 00:17:58,120
 study, learning, instruction, images,

307
00:17:58,120 --> 00:18:01,640
 suggestions, illustrations, all brought together

308
00:18:01,640 --> 00:18:05,160
 to make a meaningful experience of the word of God

309
00:18:05,160 --> 00:18:08,200
 brought alive in the hearing of the congregation.

310
00:18:08,200 --> 00:18:13,760
 And I do wonder whether a digital culture

311
00:18:13,760 --> 00:18:17,080
 could embrace that kind of communication,

312
00:18:17,080 --> 00:18:22,080
 that sense of multi-modality, multi-dimensionality,

313
00:18:22,080 --> 00:18:25,560
 given the context and culture

314
00:18:25,560 --> 00:18:27,840
 of contemporary digital engagement.

315
00:18:28,840 --> 00:18:32,840
 I'm intrigued that Justin Peterson, Charlie Kirk,

316
00:18:32,840 --> 00:18:36,480
 Glenn Scrivener in the US are very verbal,

317
00:18:36,480 --> 00:18:38,760
 are very speech-orientated,

318
00:18:38,760 --> 00:18:41,960
 rather than pushing into visuality

319
00:18:41,960 --> 00:18:44,640
 and other modes of communication,

320
00:18:44,640 --> 00:18:48,320
 using internet modes of address

321
00:18:48,320 --> 00:18:50,280
 to spread a revivalist gospel.

322
00:18:56,080 --> 00:19:00,440
 How do we explore a multi-dimensional word of God?

323
00:19:00,440 --> 00:19:09,160
 But that isn't just spiritual manipulation of the audience

324
00:19:09,160 --> 00:19:10,840
 through rhetorical speaking.

325
00:19:10,840 --> 00:19:16,000
 It's the infusion of the activity of the spirit

326
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:18,400
 into the process of the sermon delivery.

327
00:19:18,400 --> 00:19:22,680
 The presence of Jesus, who has promised

328
00:19:22,680 --> 00:19:24,600
 that where two or three are gathered,

329
00:19:24,600 --> 00:19:26,360
 he is there in their midst.

330
00:19:26,360 --> 00:19:32,400
 It's the spiritual dimension of what's happening.

331
00:19:32,400 --> 00:19:36,320
 And sometimes quite by accident, perhaps.

332
00:19:36,320 --> 00:19:40,800
 Let me give you an intriguing example.

333
00:19:40,800 --> 00:19:45,120
 Jonathan Edwards, one of the great revivalist preachers

334
00:19:45,120 --> 00:19:46,680
 in the early United States,

335
00:19:46,680 --> 00:19:49,440
 or pre the United part of the States,

336
00:19:49,440 --> 00:19:53,520
 in the colonies,

337
00:19:54,360 --> 00:19:58,240
 he was preaching in his pilgrim base in North America

338
00:19:58,240 --> 00:19:59,920
 in the early 18th century.

339
00:19:59,920 --> 00:20:04,760
 Edwards saw massive revivals,

340
00:20:04,760 --> 00:20:10,400
 which often manifested in people falling over

341
00:20:10,400 --> 00:20:13,480
 in ecstasy or rapture within the church.

342
00:20:13,480 --> 00:20:17,000
 But Edwards didn't know, really.

343
00:20:17,000 --> 00:20:19,880
 He had really poor eyesight.

344
00:20:22,800 --> 00:20:25,560
 And so he preached with his words

345
00:20:25,560 --> 00:20:27,520
 right in front of his eyes

346
00:20:27,520 --> 00:20:31,120
 with big jam-jar spectacles.

347
00:20:31,120 --> 00:20:36,480
 And he spoke in a monotone.

348
00:20:36,480 --> 00:20:39,120
 No excitement in his voice,

349
00:20:39,120 --> 00:20:42,200
 just kind of one line all the way through,

350
00:20:42,200 --> 00:20:44,960
 holding a paper up in front of him like this.

351
00:20:44,960 --> 00:20:49,640
 And you'd expect that there was no oratory,

352
00:20:49,640 --> 00:20:52,880
 there was no emotion in his voice,

353
00:20:52,880 --> 00:20:53,840
 that nothing would happen,

354
00:20:53,840 --> 00:20:56,600
 everyone would fall asleep when he took the paper down.

355
00:20:56,600 --> 00:20:59,880
 But what happened again and again and again

356
00:20:59,880 --> 00:21:04,160
 was the audience was slain in the pews or in the aisles,

357
00:21:04,160 --> 00:21:08,680
 people lying down, resting in the Lord all over the place.

358
00:21:08,680 --> 00:21:11,240
 And Jonathan Edwards hadn't created that,

359
00:21:11,240 --> 00:21:13,640
 hadn't created that psychological effect

360
00:21:13,640 --> 00:21:16,280
 or that psychiatric event, perhaps even.

361
00:21:17,360 --> 00:21:21,880
 Simply the Word of God being spoken in a simple way

362
00:21:21,880 --> 00:21:26,880
 led to this outpouring of the Spirit amongst them.

363
00:21:26,880 --> 00:21:37,840
 There was little here of the kind of later

364
00:21:37,840 --> 00:21:40,640
 Victorian bluster and performance

365
00:21:40,640 --> 00:21:42,520
 such as with Charles Spurgeon.

366
00:21:42,520 --> 00:21:46,560
 Edwards simply delivered the text.

367
00:21:47,240 --> 00:21:51,120
 God's Spirit fell upon the congregation

368
00:21:51,120 --> 00:21:53,320
 and many collapsed,

369
00:21:53,320 --> 00:21:56,760
 overcome by the presence of God in their lives.

370
00:21:56,760 --> 00:22:04,680
 It seems quite a long way from Cicero's rhetoric.

371
00:22:04,680 --> 00:22:10,120
 Instead, it's allowing the Holy Spirit

372
00:22:10,120 --> 00:22:14,160
 to be combined into and alongside

373
00:22:14,160 --> 00:22:18,080
 the words that we put together under the grace of God.

374
00:22:18,080 --> 00:22:23,560
 A way of fusing the communication of human preaching

375
00:22:23,560 --> 00:22:28,560
 with the communication of the divine in the same process.

376
00:22:28,560 --> 00:22:33,760
 As I preach, I believe God fuses His very presence,

377
00:22:33,760 --> 00:22:39,120
 His creative breath into my words,

378
00:22:40,840 --> 00:22:44,280
 into your words if you're a preacher.

379
00:22:44,280 --> 00:22:48,080
 Not because I'm special,

380
00:22:48,080 --> 00:22:51,040
 but because this is the very nature

381
00:22:51,040 --> 00:22:53,040
 of what preaching is about.

382
00:22:53,040 --> 00:22:59,240
 Preaching invites God into the rhetorical moment

383
00:22:59,240 --> 00:23:02,640
 or God invades the rhetorical moment.

384
00:23:02,640 --> 00:23:05,720
 God doesn't need to be invited anywhere.

385
00:23:05,720 --> 00:23:10,000
 God comes down and places Himself

386
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:11,800
 in that preaching moment.

387
00:23:11,800 --> 00:23:15,200
 God's very presence,

388
00:23:15,200 --> 00:23:21,160
 present in the words that are uttered by the preacher.

389
00:23:21,160 --> 00:23:29,320
 What is preaching?

390
00:23:29,320 --> 00:23:34,440
 So far, a talk based on scripture,

391
00:23:34,440 --> 00:23:38,520
 sometimes instruction, sometimes as well delight,

392
00:23:38,520 --> 00:23:41,360
 always persuasion to follow God's way.

393
00:23:41,360 --> 00:23:46,840
 A talk delivered by a human in partnership with the divine.

394
00:23:46,840 --> 00:23:52,800
 Words which publicly portray events and spiritual realities.

395
00:23:52,800 --> 00:23:57,040
 Words which take the reader back into biblical times

396
00:23:57,040 --> 00:24:01,520
 and apply those words into the here and now,

397
00:24:01,520 --> 00:24:03,720
 a journey through time.

398
00:24:03,720 --> 00:24:07,200
 This is how we were, this is how we are,

399
00:24:08,440 --> 00:24:10,640
 this is where we will be.

400
00:24:10,640 --> 00:24:27,440
 Sermons are perhaps pointless without an audience,

401
00:24:27,440 --> 00:24:29,040
 without a congregation.

402
00:24:29,040 --> 00:24:33,120
 In 2010, when we were a research center

403
00:24:33,120 --> 00:24:35,720
 at Durham University in the UK,

404
00:24:35,720 --> 00:24:38,880
 we commissioned a national poll around preaching

405
00:24:38,880 --> 00:24:40,400
 called View from the Pew.

406
00:24:40,400 --> 00:24:44,120
 60% of the people questioned

407
00:24:44,120 --> 00:24:48,120
 said that sermons provided them with a sense of God's love.

408
00:24:48,120 --> 00:24:48,960
 Great.

409
00:24:48,960 --> 00:24:54,680
 Indeed, despite the bad press for sermons in today's culture,

410
00:24:54,680 --> 00:24:56,040
 especially in the West,

411
00:24:56,040 --> 00:25:01,000
 64% regularly look forward to the sermon,

412
00:25:01,000 --> 00:25:05,120
 with another 32% sometimes looking forward to one.

413
00:25:06,120 --> 00:25:09,800
 In the terms of what the sermon did,

414
00:25:09,800 --> 00:25:11,720
 most people said that the sermons

415
00:25:11,720 --> 00:25:14,480
 tended to change how they felt.

416
00:25:14,480 --> 00:25:19,240
 In the survey, people talked of sermons

417
00:25:19,240 --> 00:25:23,280
 instructing them about Jesus and God's love.

418
00:25:23,280 --> 00:25:27,200
 Although there's a clear difference

419
00:25:27,200 --> 00:25:30,480
 between the impact of the sermon as instruction

420
00:25:30,480 --> 00:25:33,240
 and the impact of changed lives,

421
00:25:33,240 --> 00:25:37,960
 only 17% said that sermons changed their lives.

422
00:25:37,960 --> 00:25:45,040
 Although another 70% agreed that sometimes that did happen.

423
00:25:45,040 --> 00:25:49,400
 I'm not sure that Augustine or Paul

424
00:25:49,400 --> 00:25:51,840
 would have been too critical

425
00:25:51,840 --> 00:25:54,960
 after 2000 years of Christian preaching.

426
00:25:54,960 --> 00:26:01,360
 Augustine's three words, instruct, entertain, persuade,

427
00:26:01,360 --> 00:26:03,480
 also remain important

428
00:26:03,480 --> 00:26:05,920
 to the contemporary reception of the sermon.

429
00:26:05,920 --> 00:26:11,880
 So our survey suggested that 45% of listeners

430
00:26:11,880 --> 00:26:14,480
 felt sermons should educate the reader,

431
00:26:14,480 --> 00:26:17,600
 with only 12% thinking of sermons

432
00:26:17,600 --> 00:26:20,200
 that they should entertain the congregation.

433
00:26:20,200 --> 00:26:25,560
 And persuasion was down to 8% to 11%.

434
00:26:27,040 --> 00:26:29,960
 Although 78% thought that sermons

435
00:26:29,960 --> 00:26:32,880
 should challenge the congregation.

436
00:26:32,880 --> 00:26:37,480
 So in today's church in the UK,

437
00:26:37,480 --> 00:26:42,480
 which is not the same context at all as Hong Kong church,

438
00:26:42,480 --> 00:26:52,040
 people want a sermon which encourages,

439
00:26:52,040 --> 00:26:54,960
 challenges, and educates.

440
00:26:55,960 --> 00:26:58,960
 It's interesting that shortly after the survey was taken,

441
00:26:58,960 --> 00:27:02,600
 we began another on the shift of the most popular Bible verse

442
00:27:02,600 --> 00:27:06,680
 from John 3, 16 to Jeremiah 29, 11.

443
00:27:06,680 --> 00:27:11,240
 From the death of Jesus to the promise of God

444
00:27:11,240 --> 00:27:13,240
 to have good plans for us.

445
00:27:13,240 --> 00:27:18,160
 In my book on this research,

446
00:27:18,160 --> 00:27:20,200
 there's a shift that we see

447
00:27:20,200 --> 00:27:22,960
 towards what Christian Smith and Melina Lewis

448
00:27:22,960 --> 00:27:26,280
 towards what Christian Smith and Melina Lundqvist-Enten

449
00:27:26,280 --> 00:27:29,520
 called moralistic therapeutic deism.

450
00:27:29,520 --> 00:27:31,680
 The beliefs of some kind of God

451
00:27:31,680 --> 00:27:36,120
 who gave us therapy in a kind of moralistic way.

452
00:27:36,120 --> 00:27:39,040
 A God who didn't send his son to die,

453
00:27:39,040 --> 00:27:41,280
 but rather promised us all

454
00:27:41,280 --> 00:27:43,840
 that we have good plans for us ahead.

455
00:27:43,840 --> 00:27:46,720
 I can see the shift in Methodism

456
00:27:46,720 --> 00:27:50,480
 in today's contemporary situation in the UK,

457
00:27:50,480 --> 00:27:53,480
 where the Methodist church's latest tagline is,

458
00:27:53,480 --> 00:27:58,000
 God loves you unconditionally, full stop.

459
00:27:58,000 --> 00:28:06,280
 How about that for sermons being about how you feel,

460
00:28:06,280 --> 00:28:09,240
 how to change your morals?

461
00:28:09,240 --> 00:28:11,920
 Well, not change,

462
00:28:11,920 --> 00:28:14,560
 presumably keep if he loves you already.

463
00:28:14,560 --> 00:28:20,280
 A similar shift then is happening within the UK,

464
00:28:20,280 --> 00:28:22,720
 has been happening for some time.

465
00:28:22,720 --> 00:28:25,800
 A shift towards the internalization of faith

466
00:28:25,800 --> 00:28:28,160
 as noted in the work of Linda Woodhead

467
00:28:28,160 --> 00:28:30,640
 and in Abby Day's Believing Without Belonging.

468
00:28:30,640 --> 00:28:34,960
 Congregations these days want a pep talk,

469
00:28:34,960 --> 00:28:38,320
 the promise of good times to come,

470
00:28:38,320 --> 00:28:42,320
 rather than the exposition on the death

471
00:28:42,320 --> 00:28:44,640
 of a promising young man from Nazareth.

472
00:28:44,640 --> 00:28:49,520
 In an era where entertainment

473
00:28:49,520 --> 00:28:52,120
 seems to play a central part in everything we see,

474
00:28:52,120 --> 00:28:53,880
 hear and experience,

475
00:28:53,880 --> 00:28:57,920
 still over a quarter of the survey's respondents

476
00:28:57,920 --> 00:29:01,800
 believe that sermons do entertain.

477
00:29:01,800 --> 00:29:05,480
 28.3s talked of the positivity of sermons,

478
00:29:05,480 --> 00:29:08,040
 which included humor, entertainment,

479
00:29:08,040 --> 00:29:09,800
 stories and engagement.

480
00:29:09,800 --> 00:29:15,560
 Perhaps Augustine was right about delighting the audience.

481
00:29:16,520 --> 00:29:20,200
 Perhaps we're a little coy of bringing entertainment culture

482
00:29:20,200 --> 00:29:22,440
 into the experience of the church.

483
00:29:22,440 --> 00:29:32,440
 But is it better to ask what a preacher is

484
00:29:32,440 --> 00:29:34,880
 than what a sermon is?

485
00:29:34,880 --> 00:29:41,360
 Such is the argument of many contemporary homiletics tutors.

486
00:29:41,360 --> 00:29:44,200
 Here from Rob Bell,

487
00:29:46,280 --> 00:29:49,000
 an American Catholic theologian,

488
00:29:49,000 --> 00:29:52,680
 Daniela Giuppo Jerome,

489
00:29:52,680 --> 00:29:55,480
 Baptist homiletician Kenton Anderson,

490
00:29:55,480 --> 00:29:57,680
 Church of Scotland lecturer Doug Gay,

491
00:29:57,680 --> 00:29:59,960
 Episcopalian academic Annette Brown.

492
00:29:59,960 --> 00:30:03,720
 Just six books across the massive breadth

493
00:30:03,720 --> 00:30:05,080
 of contemporary writing

494
00:30:05,080 --> 00:30:09,880
 across some minority world contexts.

495
00:30:15,560 --> 00:30:19,320
 It's a problem for me that these are all European

496
00:30:19,320 --> 00:30:21,920
 or America European,

497
00:30:21,920 --> 00:30:23,360
 and I apologize for that.

498
00:30:23,360 --> 00:30:25,640
 But add your own special books,

499
00:30:25,640 --> 00:30:27,760
 add your own important books to this list.

500
00:30:27,760 --> 00:30:32,520
 All of these people write books on homiletics

501
00:30:32,520 --> 00:30:35,280
 in the culture in which I am asked to teach.

502
00:30:35,280 --> 00:30:39,320
 They prioritize the act of preaching

503
00:30:39,320 --> 00:30:41,360
 and the role of the preacher

504
00:30:41,360 --> 00:30:43,840
 rather than the nature of the sermon.

505
00:30:44,840 --> 00:30:48,160
 They argue that you need to be called to be a preacher

506
00:30:48,160 --> 00:30:50,920
 before you can start preaching a sermon.

507
00:30:50,920 --> 00:30:54,240
 Kenton Anderson there in the middle

508
00:30:54,240 --> 00:30:57,440
 starts his book with a whole chapter on

509
00:30:57,440 --> 00:31:00,040
 will you choose to preach?

510
00:31:00,040 --> 00:31:04,400
 Because it's an active decision for us to choose to preach

511
00:31:04,400 --> 00:31:06,920
 rather than simply something foist upon us.

512
00:31:06,920 --> 00:31:10,720
 God wants preachers.

513
00:31:13,840 --> 00:31:16,200
 Let me focus on two of those books.

514
00:31:16,200 --> 00:31:19,720
 Annette Brown's book,

515
00:31:19,720 --> 00:31:23,320
 let's take Annette's introductory chapter on her work

516
00:31:23,320 --> 00:31:24,920
 Preaching Jesus Christ Today.

517
00:31:24,920 --> 00:31:28,880
 Brown's seminal point is that preachers today

518
00:31:28,880 --> 00:31:31,800
 are too quick to leave scripture behind.

519
00:31:31,800 --> 00:31:36,320
 So if the lectionary text is difficult

520
00:31:36,320 --> 00:31:38,480
 rather than struggle with it

521
00:31:38,480 --> 00:31:41,320
 and wrestle like Jacob at Peniel,

522
00:31:41,320 --> 00:31:43,360
 it's easier to tell a funny story

523
00:31:43,360 --> 00:31:45,400
 about what the dog did this morning

524
00:31:45,400 --> 00:31:49,120
 and how this resonates with God's way

525
00:31:49,120 --> 00:31:50,960
 of dealing with us as sinners.

526
00:31:50,960 --> 00:31:56,240
 From the sublime, we turn to the ridiculous.

527
00:31:56,240 --> 00:32:00,200
 We don't seek to entertain, sorry,

528
00:32:00,200 --> 00:32:04,280
 we don't seek to delight, but simply to entertain.

529
00:32:04,280 --> 00:32:09,080
 We don't rise up to the peak of exegesis.

530
00:32:09,080 --> 00:32:12,120
 Instead, we plumb the depths of funny stories.

531
00:32:12,120 --> 00:32:19,520
 Brown calls the preacher back to focus on the text itself.

532
00:32:19,520 --> 00:32:23,200
 Always the text, always the Bible,

533
00:32:23,200 --> 00:32:26,600
 always God's word, not our word.

534
00:32:26,600 --> 00:32:30,400
 And she has these six different points.

535
00:32:30,400 --> 00:32:34,760
 What do I see in this text?

536
00:32:35,640 --> 00:32:38,640
 Edward and I are both Johannine scholars.

537
00:32:38,640 --> 00:32:43,040
 We've both written PhDs on John's gospel.

538
00:32:43,040 --> 00:32:46,600
 And we sat talking before this lecture started

539
00:32:46,600 --> 00:32:48,520
 about what was going on

540
00:32:48,520 --> 00:32:53,040
 and talking about his trauma studies at Edinburgh

541
00:32:53,040 --> 00:32:55,400
 and my own study into the prologue

542
00:32:55,400 --> 00:32:58,680
 and my teaching since I was a young boy.

543
00:32:58,680 --> 00:33:00,760
 And I was thinking about how I could

544
00:33:00,760 --> 00:33:02,960
 turn my own study into the prologue

545
00:33:02,960 --> 00:33:06,040
 and my teaching since upon the woman

546
00:33:06,040 --> 00:33:08,560
 caught in adultery and so on,

547
00:33:08,560 --> 00:33:11,600
 about how those trauma studies were part and parcel.

548
00:33:11,600 --> 00:33:13,800
 There's a rich moment for me

549
00:33:13,800 --> 00:33:18,280
 of connection over the word of God.

550
00:33:18,280 --> 00:33:23,280
 What does the preacher or the scholar see in this text?

551
00:33:23,280 --> 00:33:26,960
 Not just read about,

552
00:33:26,960 --> 00:33:31,120
 not just have a kind of academic relationship with,

553
00:33:31,120 --> 00:33:32,800
 not just look in different translations

554
00:33:32,800 --> 00:33:33,960
 and see what they say,

555
00:33:33,960 --> 00:33:36,440
 but how does the reader enter into the text

556
00:33:36,440 --> 00:33:39,480
 and see this text in their own eyes,

557
00:33:39,480 --> 00:33:42,000
 transport themselves to that place?

558
00:33:42,000 --> 00:33:46,400
 Alex, after what you did with the donkey,

559
00:33:46,400 --> 00:33:51,320
 perhaps you need to recreate some immersive Bible stories

560
00:33:51,320 --> 00:33:53,480
 with other animals and such things.

561
00:33:56,040 --> 00:34:02,040
 Secondly, whom do we see?

562
00:34:02,040 --> 00:34:04,160
 Where is Christ in this story?

563
00:34:04,160 --> 00:34:06,440
 Where is Christ in this passage?

564
00:34:06,440 --> 00:34:11,160
 And how do we portray Christ in our own preaching?

565
00:34:11,160 --> 00:34:15,400
 Thirdly, in a very Ignatian model,

566
00:34:15,400 --> 00:34:19,480
 what is Christ saying to me in this passage?

567
00:34:19,480 --> 00:34:22,520
 What is the word of God saying to me directly

568
00:34:22,520 --> 00:34:24,440
 in what this passage is saying?

569
00:34:24,440 --> 00:34:29,560
 But more than that, it's not just a kind of self-identity.

570
00:34:29,560 --> 00:34:32,000
 It's not about me as an individual.

571
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:35,520
 What is Christ's word saying to us,

572
00:34:35,520 --> 00:34:39,680
 to the world that we live in today?

573
00:34:39,680 --> 00:34:42,440
 In what way does the preacher become a theologian?

574
00:34:42,440 --> 00:34:48,560
 And a theologian of the broken body?

575
00:34:51,920 --> 00:34:54,600
 And then what does it all look like?

576
00:34:54,600 --> 00:34:58,080
 How do we preach that as a witness

577
00:34:58,080 --> 00:35:00,320
 to Christ in a disobedient world?

578
00:35:00,320 --> 00:35:05,480
 If we look back at my initial approach,

579
00:35:05,480 --> 00:35:08,240
 the sermon as a multidimensional activity,

580
00:35:08,240 --> 00:35:09,920
 we see similarities.

581
00:35:09,920 --> 00:35:11,960
 The preacher is someone who engages

582
00:35:11,960 --> 00:35:14,520
 with a biblical passage or a biblical theme

583
00:35:14,520 --> 00:35:16,240
 across a number of passages

584
00:35:16,240 --> 00:35:18,800
 and seeks through focusing upon Christ

585
00:35:18,800 --> 00:35:21,200
 to apply this message to themselves,

586
00:35:21,200 --> 00:35:24,960
 their congregation, to our broken world.

587
00:35:24,960 --> 00:35:27,320
 Multiple dimensions.

588
00:35:27,320 --> 00:35:29,920
 The preacher is called to be a time traveler,

589
00:35:29,920 --> 00:35:32,800
 a theologian, an artist, a historian,

590
00:35:32,800 --> 00:35:36,160
 a public commentator, a mystagogue,

591
00:35:36,160 --> 00:35:38,960
 one who reveals the very mysteries of God.

592
00:35:38,960 --> 00:35:46,360
 Doug Gay makes the same kind of multidimensional approach,

593
00:35:46,360 --> 00:35:49,080
 arguing that an artist does not so much need

594
00:35:49,080 --> 00:35:52,560
 to learn the theory of art,

595
00:35:52,560 --> 00:35:56,080
 but rather focusing on the practicing of art itself.

596
00:35:56,080 --> 00:36:00,960
 The process of selecting colors, painting media,

597
00:36:00,960 --> 00:36:03,680
 the transfer of light and color and meaning

598
00:36:03,680 --> 00:36:05,520
 from reality to canvas,

599
00:36:05,520 --> 00:36:07,600
 the development of their gift of inserting

600
00:36:07,600 --> 00:36:10,840
 their own ingenuity and personality

601
00:36:10,840 --> 00:36:13,280
 into the practice of the art itself.

602
00:36:14,960 --> 00:36:19,320
 What an image of the sermon as crafting a piece of art,

603
00:36:19,320 --> 00:36:24,440
 of shaping a pot on the potter's wheel,

604
00:36:24,440 --> 00:36:30,360
 of designing something, of writing a computer program,

605
00:36:30,360 --> 00:36:33,040
 of shaping some digital art,

606
00:36:33,040 --> 00:36:37,040
 rather than as something that's simply so word-based.

607
00:36:37,040 --> 00:36:41,800
 Preaching is the art of witnessing to the presence

608
00:36:41,800 --> 00:36:44,320
 of the cosmic Christ in all things.

609
00:36:45,320 --> 00:36:50,320
 But how do we do this within a digital age?

610
00:36:50,320 --> 00:36:53,960
 This is perhaps the big dimension,

611
00:36:53,960 --> 00:36:57,320
 which I've failed to mention so far, which is strange.

612
00:36:57,320 --> 00:37:00,480
 I have so much to do with digital culture.

613
00:37:00,480 --> 00:37:02,680
 So much of my life is about digital culture.

614
00:37:02,680 --> 00:37:05,560
 I set up an international network of people

615
00:37:05,560 --> 00:37:07,200
 looking at digital theology.

616
00:37:07,200 --> 00:37:09,720
 I've pioneered that academic program.

617
00:37:12,960 --> 00:37:16,720
 Has digitality so affected humanity

618
00:37:16,720 --> 00:37:20,480
 as to shift the basis upon which we preach

619
00:37:20,480 --> 00:37:23,800
 or the methods we should use to preach?

620
00:37:23,800 --> 00:37:26,800
 Oh, sorry.

621
00:37:26,800 --> 00:37:31,680
 I think the answer is yes and no.

622
00:37:31,680 --> 00:37:38,880
 Preaching is a divinely instituted,

623
00:37:38,880 --> 00:37:43,560
 culturally embedded process of exploration of God's word

624
00:37:43,560 --> 00:37:45,800
 within the prevailing cultures of the day.

625
00:37:45,800 --> 00:37:53,360
 So we notice similarities across the approach of Noah,

626
00:37:53,360 --> 00:37:57,000
 Moses, Miriam, Jeremiah, Jesus, Paul, Augustine,

627
00:37:57,000 --> 00:37:59,320
 Julian of Norwich, Luther, Kierkegaard,

628
00:37:59,320 --> 00:38:00,840
 Mother Teresa, Rowan Williams,

629
00:38:00,840 --> 00:38:03,400
 Nadia Botz-Weber, Annette Brown,

630
00:38:03,400 --> 00:38:05,560
 Doug Gay, Kenton Anson, all the others.

631
00:38:06,560 --> 00:38:09,280
 Culture has its part to play,

632
00:38:09,280 --> 00:38:11,520
 but the preacher's role remains the same.

633
00:38:11,520 --> 00:38:15,000
 To witness to the role of Christ

634
00:38:15,000 --> 00:38:18,160
 through the preacher in instruction, delight,

635
00:38:18,160 --> 00:38:21,360
 and influence in and upon and through our lives.

636
00:38:21,360 --> 00:38:26,240
 The role of the preacher is to take the word of God

637
00:38:26,240 --> 00:38:29,600
 and seek to show through instruction, delight, and sway

638
00:38:29,600 --> 00:38:33,240
 how God guides us to be different people.

639
00:38:33,240 --> 00:38:36,040
 How God guides us to be different people.

640
00:38:36,040 --> 00:38:40,120
 To be agents of light,

641
00:38:40,120 --> 00:38:45,480
 to be representatives of God in whatever culture we find.

642
00:38:45,480 --> 00:38:51,240
 This is patiently true.

643
00:38:51,240 --> 00:38:53,880
 It's what we see in the world around us.

644
00:38:53,880 --> 00:38:55,520
 It's what we see in history.

645
00:38:55,520 --> 00:38:59,240
 We see it in Paul's own use of that phrase

646
00:38:59,240 --> 00:39:00,680
 in Galatians 3.1,

647
00:39:02,040 --> 00:39:04,600
 when neither they nor Paul have been eyewitnesses,

648
00:39:04,600 --> 00:39:07,560
 they are called to witness the resurrection

649
00:39:07,560 --> 00:39:10,640
 before their eyes, the crucifixion before their eyes.

650
00:39:10,640 --> 00:39:14,800
 Preaching takes us to a different place.

651
00:39:14,800 --> 00:39:22,760
 Myriad cultures have come and gone,

652
00:39:22,760 --> 00:39:26,120
 but the witness of Christ in the world remains consistent.

653
00:39:26,120 --> 00:39:29,000
 He died for us.

654
00:39:30,200 --> 00:39:33,160
 We are called to accept that fact

655
00:39:33,160 --> 00:39:37,320
 and be transformed by his presence in our lives.

656
00:39:37,320 --> 00:39:40,320
 But as this slide shows,

657
00:39:40,320 --> 00:39:43,240
 digital culture can distract us from the message of God.

658
00:39:43,240 --> 00:39:47,080
 After all, digitality is best described

659
00:39:47,080 --> 00:39:49,800
 as a distraction culture,

660
00:39:49,800 --> 00:39:52,640
 offering myriad opportunities

661
00:39:52,640 --> 00:39:56,080
 to be pushed away from the core focus

662
00:39:56,080 --> 00:39:58,360
 and be delighted by many other things,

663
00:39:58,360 --> 00:40:01,760
 randomly different things, entertainingly different things.

664
00:40:01,760 --> 00:40:05,080
 Look, here's another offering.

665
00:40:05,080 --> 00:40:07,400
 Here's another bit of entertainment for you.

666
00:40:07,400 --> 00:40:13,680
 Angela Gurel in her book about navigating digitality

667
00:40:13,680 --> 00:40:17,600
 talks about the importance of our response to that fact,

668
00:40:17,600 --> 00:40:19,360
 to digital culture,

669
00:40:19,360 --> 00:40:23,120
 and queries whether we reject it out of hand,

670
00:40:23,120 --> 00:40:25,720
 I'm not having anything to do with it,

671
00:40:25,720 --> 00:40:28,360
 we embrace it without any critique,

672
00:40:28,360 --> 00:40:34,040
 or we end up in some form of homesickness, nostalgia,

673
00:40:34,040 --> 00:40:38,400
 wondering what happened to the world that we believed in,

674
00:40:38,400 --> 00:40:41,000
 the world that we lived in.

675
00:40:41,000 --> 00:40:47,360
 Digitality has the potential to distract us,

676
00:40:47,360 --> 00:40:50,560
 destabilize us, deconstruct us.

677
00:40:52,200 --> 00:40:54,880
 But at the same time, it can equip us,

678
00:40:54,880 --> 00:40:58,880
 educate us, and engage us in better learning,

679
00:40:58,880 --> 00:41:01,760
 connect us with millions of new friends,

680
00:41:01,760 --> 00:41:05,480
 transcend our own limitations or abilities.

681
00:41:05,480 --> 00:41:11,920
 Swedish theologian Amanda Lagerqvist

682
00:41:11,920 --> 00:41:14,040
 talks about this in her work,

683
00:41:14,040 --> 00:41:16,760
 where she goes back to Heidegger's concept

684
00:41:16,760 --> 00:41:19,120
 of Geworfenheit or throneness.

685
00:41:20,320 --> 00:41:23,840
 He argued that we're each thrown into our existence,

686
00:41:23,840 --> 00:41:26,280
 we can feel we have no anchors,

687
00:41:26,280 --> 00:41:29,120
 no foundations, no real presence.

688
00:41:29,120 --> 00:41:35,520
 Heidegger wasn't talking about digital culture, of course,

689
00:41:35,520 --> 00:41:39,200
 but of the very basics of human existence,

690
00:41:39,200 --> 00:41:41,720
 thrown into the midst of life,

691
00:41:41,720 --> 00:41:44,280
 which needs living whatever the context.

692
00:41:44,280 --> 00:41:49,040
 Lagerqvist applies this to digital existence

693
00:41:49,040 --> 00:41:51,920
 in this paragraph, I don't think I've included it.

694
00:41:51,920 --> 00:41:52,760
 Yes, I have.

695
00:41:52,760 --> 00:41:57,200
 I've posited a human being for the digital human,

696
00:41:57,200 --> 00:42:00,320
 I've posited a human being for the digital human condition

697
00:42:00,320 --> 00:42:04,080
 as an exister, that is a precarious,

698
00:42:04,080 --> 00:42:07,000
 embodied, relational, mortal creature,

699
00:42:07,000 --> 00:42:09,360
 sometimes at last, bewildered,

700
00:42:09,360 --> 00:42:11,920
 and in search for meaning before the abyss.

701
00:42:11,920 --> 00:42:16,440
 She's imbricated in social technological ensembles,

702
00:42:16,440 --> 00:42:19,440
 traversing these terrains more or less successfully

703
00:42:19,440 --> 00:42:21,920
 in search of what may be cautiously termed

704
00:42:21,920 --> 00:42:23,880
 existential security.

705
00:42:23,880 --> 00:42:28,560
 Existential media studies actually requires

706
00:42:28,560 --> 00:42:31,720
 a paradigmatic change of casting.

707
00:42:31,720 --> 00:42:35,120
 The principal inhabitant of the digital ecology,

708
00:42:35,120 --> 00:42:37,360
 our principal subject in media studies,

709
00:42:37,360 --> 00:42:40,200
 is not a savvy early adopter,

710
00:42:40,200 --> 00:42:42,840
 but the human being who sometimes stumbles,

711
00:42:42,840 --> 00:42:46,440
 falls, misunderstands, struggles,

712
00:42:46,440 --> 00:42:49,840
 is vulnerable, hurting, speechless,

713
00:42:49,840 --> 00:42:51,560
 and finds no solution.

714
00:42:51,560 --> 00:42:56,360
 But she may also experience moments of ultimate meaning,

715
00:42:56,360 --> 00:42:59,720
 community, support, and fullness

716
00:42:59,720 --> 00:43:01,960
 as she navigates through the torrents

717
00:43:01,960 --> 00:43:03,760
 of our digital existence.

718
00:43:10,000 --> 00:43:13,160
 The thing that struck me about Larkin's model

719
00:43:13,160 --> 00:43:17,320
 is how much that refers to so many cultures,

720
00:43:17,320 --> 00:43:20,360
 and that's why I was very hesitant to say

721
00:43:20,360 --> 00:43:22,840
 this is what digital culture is doing,

722
00:43:22,840 --> 00:43:25,360
 and therefore preaching must change.

723
00:43:25,360 --> 00:43:27,360
 There have been so many cultural shifts

724
00:43:27,360 --> 00:43:29,600
 over so many millennia,

725
00:43:29,600 --> 00:43:33,400
 and still preaching has remained the same basic model.

726
00:43:33,400 --> 00:43:36,880
 Preaching has been the explanation of the word of God

727
00:43:36,880 --> 00:43:39,120
 to the people, the gift of the Holy Spirit

728
00:43:39,120 --> 00:43:40,720
 through that word to a new,

729
00:43:40,720 --> 00:43:43,240
 an invitation to a new way of living.

730
00:43:43,240 --> 00:43:47,440
 We all struggle.

731
00:43:47,440 --> 00:43:51,480
 We all battle with the exigencies of our existence,

732
00:43:51,480 --> 00:43:53,800
 some more successfully than others.

733
00:43:53,800 --> 00:43:58,400
 But humanity has ever since humanity began.

734
00:43:58,400 --> 00:43:59,800
 Look at Genesis.

735
00:43:59,800 --> 00:44:03,680
 We all seek a way of making sense,

736
00:44:03,680 --> 00:44:05,880
 and for those of us in the Christian faith,

737
00:44:05,880 --> 00:44:09,520
 we believe the best sense is made in God's gift of his Son

738
00:44:09,520 --> 00:44:10,920
 to save the world.

739
00:44:10,920 --> 00:44:17,120
 Preaching across multiple cultures in multiple millennia

740
00:44:17,120 --> 00:44:22,560
 has been the way of focusing on this gift, this presence,

741
00:44:22,560 --> 00:44:25,320
 Christ in us, the hope of glory.

742
00:44:25,320 --> 00:44:31,600
 We mustn't make digitality, coming to the end,

743
00:44:31,600 --> 00:44:33,280
 to be more than it is.

744
00:44:34,360 --> 00:44:36,600
 It's an existential problem.

745
00:44:36,600 --> 00:44:39,480
 But so is the fall of the Roman Empire,

746
00:44:39,480 --> 00:44:41,640
 the rise of China, Japan, Korea,

747
00:44:41,640 --> 00:44:43,960
 the impact of colonialism and slave trade,

748
00:44:43,960 --> 00:44:46,440
 the rise of European-led empire building,

749
00:44:46,440 --> 00:44:48,720
 the World Wars, the Atomic Age, the '60s,

750
00:44:48,720 --> 00:44:49,640
 the end of British rule,

751
00:44:49,640 --> 00:44:52,480
 the impending crisis of environmental degradation,

752
00:44:52,480 --> 00:44:55,920
 the upheaval of Trumpianism, and other forms of neo-fascism.

753
00:44:55,920 --> 00:45:01,440
 Cultures are here and gone in the blink of an eye.

754
00:45:02,600 --> 00:45:06,680
 But when they are here, they seem to change everything.

755
00:45:06,680 --> 00:45:08,960
 They change our ideologies,

756
00:45:08,960 --> 00:45:13,440
 but in fact, they change nothing on God's terms.

757
00:45:13,440 --> 00:45:16,920
 As Annette Brown pointed out,

758
00:45:16,920 --> 00:45:19,760
 part of the role of preaching is to pay witness,

759
00:45:19,760 --> 00:45:23,440
 continued witness, to the role of Christ

760
00:45:23,440 --> 00:45:26,880
 as healer of broken worlds and broken lives.

761
00:45:26,880 --> 00:45:29,760
 Whenever and wherever and however they are broken,

762
00:45:29,760 --> 00:45:33,920
 preaching isn't really impacted by any specific culture.

763
00:45:33,920 --> 00:45:39,720
 Christ's word, God's message, remains across the years.

764
00:45:39,720 --> 00:45:43,240
 God continues to speak.

765
00:45:43,240 --> 00:45:50,720
 Yes, there are elements of digitality, fringe elements,

766
00:45:50,720 --> 00:45:53,800
 which may impact the way that we preach.

767
00:45:53,800 --> 00:45:56,160
 There are images in the slide deck which explore this.

768
00:45:56,160 --> 00:45:59,360
 Here's one of Professor Maggie Dorn's exploration

769
00:45:59,360 --> 00:46:02,920
 of digitality in our book, "Messier Day at the Digital Age,"

770
00:46:02,920 --> 00:46:05,920
 a great book which explores this topic in much greater detail.

771
00:46:05,920 --> 00:46:10,320
 She talks about the plurality

772
00:46:10,320 --> 00:46:13,480
 of technological communications over millennia,

773
00:46:13,480 --> 00:46:17,080
 the need to prioritize the use of the appropriate tool

774
00:46:17,080 --> 00:46:19,680
 for the event you're to preach at,

775
00:46:19,680 --> 00:46:22,360
 to speak the language of your heart,

776
00:46:22,360 --> 00:46:26,360
 your culture, shared with your congregation,

777
00:46:26,360 --> 00:46:28,680
 always being prepared to give an answer

778
00:46:28,680 --> 00:46:31,000
 to everyone who asks you to give a reason

779
00:46:31,000 --> 00:46:33,120
 for the hope that you have,

780
00:46:33,120 --> 00:46:37,280
 but to do that with gentleness and respect.

781
00:46:37,280 --> 00:46:40,080
 Digital culture focuses on images,

782
00:46:40,080 --> 00:46:42,360
 on digital artifacts, on videos,

783
00:46:42,360 --> 00:46:45,280
 of sharing culture of diversity,

784
00:46:45,280 --> 00:46:49,120
 but also now on anti-woke culture.

785
00:46:49,120 --> 00:46:51,080
 It's focused on teamwork,

786
00:46:51,080 --> 00:46:54,880
 but now also on the almost fascist power

787
00:46:54,880 --> 00:46:56,880
 within the individual.

788
00:46:57,880 --> 00:47:00,880
 Such cultural resonances

789
00:47:00,880 --> 00:47:04,880
 may help us to get the message across,

790
00:47:04,880 --> 00:47:08,880
 but the point is, what's your message in the first place?

791
00:47:08,880 --> 00:47:12,880
 Are you trying to ensure that that message,

792
00:47:12,880 --> 00:47:15,880
 God's message, is what's heard?

793
00:47:15,880 --> 00:47:20,880
 In the end, preaching is a gift from God,

794
00:47:20,880 --> 00:47:24,880
 an opportunity to learn what the Father is saying to us

795
00:47:24,880 --> 00:47:28,880
 out of his word through his spirit for our own times.

796
00:47:28,880 --> 00:47:31,880
 We are witnesses of this,

797
00:47:31,880 --> 00:47:36,880
 and are called to proclaim that word

798
00:47:36,880 --> 00:47:39,880
 to his people and to the world,

799
00:47:39,880 --> 00:47:44,880
 and thus within and beyond the dominant cultures of our times.

800
00:47:44,880 --> 00:47:53,880
 If you're thinking of using an AI for your preach,

801
00:47:53,880 --> 00:47:56,880
 listen to the lecture last Friday.

802
00:47:56,880 --> 00:47:59,880
 Listen to what the donkey has to say.

803
00:47:59,880 --> 00:48:05,880
 It's interesting that one of my, two of my friends' research

804
00:48:05,880 --> 00:48:09,880
 they've done in Sweden, where they talked to a load of Swedish theologians

805
00:48:09,880 --> 00:48:11,880
 who have used AI in preaching,

806
00:48:11,880 --> 00:48:15,880
 not one of those preachers

807
00:48:15,880 --> 00:48:19,880
 actually used the words given to them by AI.

808
00:48:19,880 --> 00:48:24,880
 They used the suggestions from the AI bots

809
00:48:24,880 --> 00:48:27,880
 to give them a mood sense of what it was about,

810
00:48:27,880 --> 00:48:30,880
 a mood board of what it was about,

811
00:48:30,880 --> 00:48:33,880
 to give them ideas about what they could preach,

812
00:48:33,880 --> 00:48:38,880
 that they then prayed over and sought to find God's inspiration.

813
00:48:38,880 --> 00:48:43,880
 But note, as I say, what I said last week,

814
00:48:43,880 --> 00:48:47,880
 cheating makes you less intelligent.

815
00:48:47,880 --> 00:48:50,880
 (Laughter)

816
00:48:50,880 --> 00:48:53,880
 Even worse in Christianity,

817
00:48:53,880 --> 00:48:56,880
 going to an AI is no answer,

818
00:48:56,880 --> 00:49:01,880
 is no response to going to God, your God,

819
00:49:01,880 --> 00:49:08,880
 who offers you all the grace and love he has in abundance.

820
00:49:08,880 --> 00:49:15,880
 Why would you go to Gemini or GPT

821
00:49:15,880 --> 00:49:20,880
 when you can call on the Holy Spirit to guide your preaching?

822
00:49:20,880 --> 00:49:27,880
 Remember, AI is trained on Reddit, on emails, on Wikipedia,

823
00:49:27,880 --> 00:49:30,880
 on all the trash of the news groups,

824
00:49:30,880 --> 00:49:33,880
 as well as millions of authored books that haven't been paid for

825
00:49:33,880 --> 00:49:36,880
 and no money has gone to the authors.

826
00:49:36,880 --> 00:49:40,880
 What do you want your AI sermons to be built on?

827
00:49:40,880 --> 00:49:46,880
 The trash pile? The stench of fossil fuels?

828
00:49:46,880 --> 00:49:50,880
 The continued devastation of God's world?

829
00:49:50,880 --> 00:49:54,880
 Why not trust God instead?

830
00:49:54,880 --> 00:49:57,880
 Why not go to the Holy Spirit?

831
00:49:57,880 --> 00:50:02,880
 Why not wrestle with the Bible text rather than wrestling with Grok?

832
00:50:02,880 --> 00:50:09,880
 As Doug Gay says, "Preaching is a demanding privilege.

833
00:50:09,880 --> 00:50:15,880
 It requires but does not depend on the best of our skill and creativity.

834
00:50:15,880 --> 00:50:20,880
 It also requires more integrity, wisdom and love

835
00:50:20,880 --> 00:50:23,880
 than most of us have to bring to it."

836
00:50:23,880 --> 00:50:32,880
 Preaching in the beginning and in the end is a gift from God.

837
00:50:32,880 --> 00:50:37,880
 Preaching in the beginning and in the end is a gift given by God.

838
00:50:37,880 --> 00:50:41,880
 And God provides all we need to make preaching in a digital age

839
00:50:41,880 --> 00:50:45,880
 both something we can be called to

840
00:50:45,880 --> 00:50:49,880
 and something which can be received and delivered

841
00:50:49,880 --> 00:50:52,880
 within the grace that he gives to us.

842
00:50:52,880 --> 00:50:58,880
 Being a digital age is a gift from God.

843
00:50:58,880 --> 00:51:02,880
 It's a gift he gives to us.

844
00:51:02,880 --> 00:51:06,880
 Be a great preacher.

845
00:51:06,880 --> 00:51:13,880
 And if you can, adapt to the culture in which God has put you.

846
00:51:13,880 --> 00:51:18,880
 Remember Jonathan Edwards, he was a terrible preacher.

847
00:51:18,880 --> 00:51:22,880
 But God still moved powerfully in his ministry.

848
00:51:22,880 --> 00:51:26,880
 God changed the lives of thousands of people

849
00:51:26,880 --> 00:51:30,880
 in the early America.

850
00:51:30,880 --> 00:51:37,880
 Be a great preacher.

851
00:51:37,880 --> 00:51:41,880
 And if you can, adapt to the culture.

852
00:51:41,880 --> 00:51:43,880
 But in the end, be a great preacher

853
00:51:43,880 --> 00:51:49,880
 by listening out for what God wants you to be as a preacher.

854
00:51:49,880 --> 00:51:53,880
 Be the person that God wants you to be,

855
00:51:53,880 --> 00:51:55,880
 not what AI wants you to be.

856
00:51:55,880 --> 00:51:57,880
 Thank you.

857
